    type: 'problem/solution',
    topic: 'Crime',
    question: 'Crime rates are increasing in many cities around the world. What do you think are the main causes of this trend and what measures can governments take to reduce crime?',
    modelAnswer: 'Escalating urban crime rates represent a complex societal challenge rooted in interconnected economic, social, and environmental factors. Addressing this issue requires comprehensive strategies that tackle both immediate symptoms and underlying causes.\n\nSeveral interconnected factors drive rising crime rates. Economic inequality remains a primary driver, as marginalized communities with limited economic opportunities often experience higher crime rates. Youth unemployment, in particular, creates conditions where criminal activity becomes an attractive alternative. Urban decay and inadequate social services in disadvantaged neighborhoods further erode community cohesion, weakening informal social controls that traditionally deter crime. Substance abuse—fueled by drug trafficking networks—creates cycles of addiction and criminal behavior. Additionally, rapid urbanization without corresponding infrastructure development can foster anonymity and social disconnection.\n\nGovernments must implement multi-pronged strategies to combat crime effectively. Investing in education and vocational training programs provides pathways to legitimate employment, addressing root economic causes. Community policing initiatives that build trust between law enforcement and residents can improve crime prevention through collaborative problem-solving. Targeted social programs addressing youth at risk—including mentorship and after-school activities—can divert young people from criminal paths. Rehabilitation-focused criminal justice reforms, including restorative justice programs and post-release support, reduce recidivism rates. Urban renewal projects that revitalize neglected neighborhoods can strengthen community bonds and improve safety.\n\nIn conclusion, reducing urban crime demands coordinated action across multiple sectors. By combining economic development, community engagement, and innovative criminal justice approaches, governments can create safer environments where crime becomes less attractive and communities can thrive.',
    modelAnswerCN: '不断上升的城市犯罪率代表了一个复杂的社会挑战，其根源在于相互关联的经济、社会和环境因素。解决这个问题需要综合战略，既要解决直接症状，也要解决根本原因。\n\n几个相互关联的因素推动了犯罪率的上升。经济不平等仍然是主要驱动力，因为经济机会有限的边缘化社区往往犯罪率较高。特别是青年失业造成了犯罪活动成为有吸引力的替代选择的条件。弱势社区的城市衰败和社会服务不足进一步削弱了社区凝聚力，削弱了传统上阻止犯罪的非正式社会控制。药物滥用——在贩毒网络的推动下——造成了成瘾和犯罪行为的循环。此外，没有相应基础设施发展的快速城市化会助长匿名性和社会脱节。\n\n政府必须实施多管齐下的战略来有效打击犯罪。投资教育和职业培训计划为合法就业提供了途径，解决了根本的经济原因。建立执法部门和居民之间信任的社区警务举措可以通过协作解决问题来改善犯罪预防。针对高危青年的有针对性的社会计划——包括辅导和课后活动——可以让年轻人远离犯罪道路。以康复为重点的刑事司法改革，包括恢复性司法计划和释放后支持，降低了累犯率。振兴被忽视社区的城市更新项目可以加强社区纽带并提高安全性。\n\n总之，减少城市犯罪需要多个部门的协调行动。通过结合经济发展、社区参与和创新的刑事司法方法，政府可以创造更安全的环境，使犯罪变得不那么有吸引力，社区能够蓬勃发展。',
    bandScore: 'Band 8.5',
    keywords: ['crime', 'urban', 'poverty', 'education', 'community', 'rehabilitation']
