    question: 'Some people think that individuals should pay for their plastic waste, while others believe the government should be responsible. Discuss both views and give your opinion.',
    modelAnswer: 'The plastic waste crisis demands comprehensive solutions addressing both individual behavior and systemic policy, with effective approaches requiring shared responsibility across multiple stakeholders.\n\nArguments for individual payment emphasize behavioral economics principles. Financial disincentives like plastic bag taxes and bottle deposits have proven effective at reducing single-use plastic consumption. When consumers bear the full cost of plastic waste, they make more conscious consumption choices, seeking alternatives and reducing unnecessary plastic use. The polluter-pays principle creates fairness, ensuring those who generate waste bear its costs rather than society as a whole. Individual payment systems can generate revenue dedicated to waste management and recycling infrastructure. Personal responsibility campaigns foster environmental consciousness and sustainable habits. Financial accountability creates immediate feedback loops connecting consumption to consequences.\n\nProponents of government responsibility highlight systemic dimensions of the plastic crisis. Plastic production and packaging decisions are made by corporations, not individual consumers. Governments have regulatory authority to ban problematic plastics, mandate recycled content, and require producer responsibility. Public waste management systems require government investment and coordination. Governments can implement comprehensive solutions: extended producer responsibility legislation, standardized recycling systems, and infrastructure development. Individual-focused approaches unfairly burden consumers while letting corporations off the hook for creating plastic products. Governments have the scale and resources to address the crisis effectively through policy and infrastructure.\n\nIn my considered view, effective plastic waste reduction requires both individual and government action rather than choosing between them. Governments must implement systemic policies: banning unnecessary single-use plastics, mandating producer responsibility, and investing in recycling infrastructure. Simultaneously, individual financial incentives like bottle deposits and plastic fees encourage behavioral change. Corporations must redesign packaging and take responsibility for product end-of-life. The most effective strategies create shared responsibility: governments set the framework through policy, corporations redesign products and systems, and individuals make conscious consumption choices. When all stakeholders contribute, comprehensive solutions become possible.',
    modelAnswerCN: '塑料废物危机需要解决个人行为和系统政策的综合解决方案，有效方法需要多个利益相关者分担责任。\n\n个人支付的论点强调行为经济学原则。财务抑制措施如塑料袋税和瓶子押金已被证明有效减少一次性塑料消费。当消费者承担塑料废物的全部成本时，他们做出更有意识的消费选择，寻求替代品并减少不必要的塑料使用。污染者付费原则创造公平，确保产生废物的人承担其成本而不是整个社会。个人支付系统可以产生专门用于废物管理和回收基础设施的收入。个人责任运动培养环境意识和可持续习惯。财务问责创造连接消费和后果的即时反馈循环。\n\n政府责任的支持者强调塑料危机的系统维度。塑料生产和包装决定由公司而非个人消费者做出。政府有监管权力禁止有问题的塑料，强制回收内容，并要求生产者责任。公共废物管理系统需要政府投资和协调。政府可以实施综合解决方案：延伸生产者责任立法、标准化回收系统和基础设施发展。以个人为中心的方法不公平地给消费者带来负担，同时让公司对创造塑料产品免于责任。政府有规模和资源通过政策和基础设施有效解决危机。\n\n在我深思熟虑的观点中，有效的塑料废物减少需要个人和政府行动而不是在它们之间做出选择。政府必须实施系统性政策：禁止不必要的一次性塑料，强制生产者责任，并投资回收基础设施。同时，个人财务激励如瓶子押金和塑料费用鼓励行为改变。公司必须重新设计包装并对产品生命周期结束负责。最有效的策略创造共同责任：政府通过政策设定框架，公司重新设计产品和系统，个人做出有意识的消费选择。当所有利益相关者贡献时，综合解决方案成为可能。',
    bandScore: 'Band 8.5',
    keywords: ['environment', 'plastic', 'waste', 'sustainability', 'government', 'responsibility']
